-----------ALGO WITH Example-------------
Algorithm: Next Permutation

Goal:
Rearrange the numbers into the next lexicographically greater permutation.
If such permutation does not exist, rearrange it to the lowest possible order
(sorted ascending).

Idea:
Find the first position from the right where the sequence stops increasing.
Swap that element with the next greater element on its right.
Finally reverse the part after that position.

Steps:

1. Traverse from right to left to find the breakpoint.
      breakpoint = first index i where nums[i] < nums[i+1]

2. If no breakpoint exists (array is completely descending):
      reverse the entire array and return.

3. Otherwise find the smallest element greater than nums[breakpoint]
   from the right side of the array.

4. Swap that element with nums[breakpoint].

5. Reverse the part of the array after the breakpoint.

This ensures the next lexicographically larger permutation.


Example:

nums = [1,3,2]


Step 1: Find breakpoint

Traverse from right:

Index | Value | ele | Condition
--------------------------------
2     | 2     | -∞  | update ele = 2
1     | 3     | 2   | update ele = 3
0     | 1     | 3   | 3 > 1 → breakpoint = 0

Breakpoint index = 0
Value = 1


Step 2: Find next greater element from right

Elements right of breakpoint:
[3,2]

Smallest element greater than 1 is 2.

Swap:

[2,3,1]


Step 3: Reverse the right part

Reverse elements after index 0.

Before reverse:
[2,3,1]

Right part:
[3,1]

After reverse:
[1,3]


Final array:

[2,1,3]


Result:
Next permutation of [1,3,2] is [2,1,3]


Special Case Example:

nums = [3,2,1]

No breakpoint exists because the array is completely decreasing.

So reverse whole array:

[3,2,1] → [1,2,3]


Time Complexity: O(n)
Space Complexity: O(1)
